your sick child, who

00:08:24.400 --> 00:08:26.440
was suffering from diarrhea.

00:08:26.440 --> 00:08:30.610
And your thoughts are
consumed with her,

00:08:30.610 --> 00:08:32.530
because you don't
know what to do.

00:08:32.530 --> 00:08:34.870
The nearest hospital
is about five miles,

00:08:34.870 --> 00:08:38.059
you don't have the money to
take your child to the hospital.

00:08:38.059 --> 00:08:42.059
You don't have access
to any physician nearby.

00:08:42.059 --> 00:08:46.230
So what do you do
in that situation?

00:08:46.230 --> 00:08:47.960
Particularly when you
know that about one

00:08:47.960 --> 00:08:50.030
out of five children
in your community

00:08:50.030 --> 00:08:54.290
dies suffering from diarrhea.

00:08:54.290 --> 00:08:57.980
Dehydration that's caused
from diarrhea and cholera

00:08:57.980 --> 00:09:01.850
was one of the primary
killers of child

00:09:01.850 --> 00:09:04.490
under five in Bangladesh.

00:09:04.490 --> 00:09:08.750
About one out of seven children
in Bangladesh right after war

00:09:08.750 --> 00:09:12.780
would actually won't make
it to their fifth birthday.

00:09:12.780 --> 00:09:15.590
So when that's the
scenario you're working on,

00:09:15.590 --> 00:09:21.830
actually this kind of related
of why we had so many children,

00:09:21.830 --> 00:09:23.720
each household had so
many children in there,

00:09:23.720 --> 00:09:26.060
because if you don't know
how many would survive,

00:09:26.060 --> 00:09:29.061
you actually don't think about
family planning that much.

00:09:29.061 --> 00:09:30.560
Actually recently,
there was a quote

00:09:30.560 --> 00:09:33.050
by Melinda Gates
the other day, who

00:09:33.050 --> 00:09:35.480
highlighted that "if parents
believe their children

00:09:35.480 --> 00:09:37.700
will survive and if they
have the power to time

00:09:37.700 --> 00:09:40.640
and space their
pregnancies, that they would

00:09:40.640 --> 00:09:42.750
choose to have fewer children."

00:09:42.750 --> 00:09:44.870
So parents living in
poverty in rural Bangladesh

00:09:44.870 --> 00:09:48.170
didn't have control of what
their children's lives are

00:09:48.170 --> 00:09:50.510
or their futures.

00:09:50.510 --> 00:09:56.150
So it wasn't that there wasn't
a solution available, there was.

00:09:56.150 --> 00:09:59.870
Actually in the 60s, there was
a breakthrough in treatment

00:09:59.870 --> 00:10:01.010
for diarrhea, right?

00:10:01.010 --> 00:10:06.500
A concoction of
water, sugar and salt

00:10:06.500 --> 00:10:10.490
called oral rehydration
therapy, or ORT was tested

00:10:10.490 --> 00:10:12.590
by a group of researchers.

00:10:12.590 --> 00:10:16.310
However this
concoction, if given

00:10:16.310 --> 00:10:18.420
to the children
at the right time,

00:10:18.420 --> 00:10:22.190
would actually save 96.5%
of the children, as opposed

00:10:22.190 --> 00:10:25.490
to 70% who would not make it.

00:10:25.490 --> 00:10:27.300
But there was another problem.

00:10:27.300 --> 00:10:30.560
The treatment was out of
reach for poor families

00:10:30.560 --> 00:10:33.560
and remained mostly
in the hospitals.

00:10:33.560 --> 00:10:38.450
Because one, you had to
get the proportion right.

00:10:38.450 --> 00:10:43.190
The researchers did have
the idea that at some point,

00:10:43.190 --> 00:10:46.490
they will market
it and they will

00:10:46.490 --> 00:10:49.190
make the instruction
available for people,

00:10:49.190 --> 00:10:51.650
but when you have
illiterate mothers

00:10:51.650 --> 00:10:53.390
all around the country,
the instructions

00:10:53.390 --> 00:10:55.250
actually not very useful.

00:10:55.250 --> 00:10:59.780
When you have instructions about
giving spoons and measurements

00:10:59.780 --> 00:11:02.380
right, when most
of the households

00:11:02.380 --> 00:11:06.140
don't have even spoons,
doesn't really work.

00:11:06.140 --> 00:11:09.372
So what do you do in
that kind of situation?

00:11:09.372 --> 00:11:11.330
Because if you don't get
the measurement right,

00:11:11.330 --> 00:11:14.340
if you have too much salt,
it may kill your baby.

00:11:14.340 --> 00:11:16.310
If you have too much
sugar, it may actually

00:11:16.310 --> 00:11:20.690
reverse the effect
of the ORT saline.

00:11:20.690 --> 00:11:25.100
So that's where, I guess, the
power of delivery comes in.

00:11:25.100 --> 00:11:28.730
Around that time, BRAC
was about 10 years old.

00:11:28.730 --> 00:11:31.780
And there was a guy
called Sir Fazle Hasan

00:11:31.780 --> 00:11:37.610
Abed who moved back from London,
leaving his cushy job at Shell

00:11:37.610 --> 00:11:41.180
Oil, and decided
that he was going

00:11:41.180 --> 00:11:43.400
to actually work
towards rebuilding

00:11:43.400 --> 00:11:45.320
the country after the war.

00:11:45.320 --> 00:11:48.770
And pretty soon, the
relief organization

00:11:48.770 --> 00:11:55.700
actually slowly expanded into
other development activities.

00:11:55.700 --> 00:11:58.700
And he was from
the private sector,

00:11:58.700 --> 00:12:01.820
and he understood
scale very well,

00:12:01.820 --> 00:12:04.170
and he was all about
problem solving.

00:12:04.170 --> 00:12:06.680
So when he heard about the
problem, one of the things

00:12:06.680 --> 00:12:10.130
that he tried, he started
experimenting in his kitchen

00:12:10.130 --> 00:12:13.100
with unrefined
sugar known as gur

00:12:13.100 --> 00:12:18.740
in Bangladesh, which is fairly
well available in rural areas.

00:12:18.740 --> 00:12:22.160
So he found out that
about three finger pinch

00:12:22.160 --> 00:12:26.810
of salt, a handful
of sugar, gur,

00:12:26.810 --> 00:12:31.730
and half a liter of boiled water
actually can make the same,

00:12:31.730 --> 00:12:35.270
have the same effect that
this World Health Organization

00:12:35.270 --> 00:12:40.330
that came up with the antidote
for, the ORT solution.

00:12:40.330 --> 00:12:46.520
So that's how easy to
make solution arrived.

00:12:46.520 --> 00:12:48.710
But then how do you
actually teach it

00:12:48.710 --> 00:12:50.936
to the rest of the country?

00:12:50.936 --> 00:12:52.310
How do you actually
go to mothers

00:12:52.310 --> 00:12:54.500
and tell them that this
is actually going to work,

00:12:54.500 --> 00:12:55.870
and this is what you should do?

00:12:55.870 --> 00:12:58.940
So that's where the
biggest challenge came in.

00:12:58.940 --> 00:13:04.310
And World Bank's president
recently said the quote

00:13:04.310 --> 00:13:07.850
that "it's not the question
of what to deliver,

00:13:07.850 --> 00:13:10.960
it's about it's about
how to deliver it."

00:13:10.960 --> 00:13:13.820
In the social
development space, it's

00:13:13.820 --> 00:13:18.020
all about not innovation
itself, but how do you actually

00:13:18.020 --> 00:13:19.670
deliver the innovation.

00:13:19.670 --> 00:13:23.600
So a media advocacy
campaign wouldn't

00:13:23.600 --> 00:13:26.480
have worked at that time
because only 20% of people

00:13:26.480 --> 00:13:29.610
have access to radio
and television.

00:13:29.610 --> 00:13:32.900
So it would have to be
sandals on the ground.

00:13:32.900 --> 00:13:36.290
People talking to people,
people changing behaviors.

00:13:36.290 --> 00:13:38.210
So that's what
BRAC started to do.

00:13:38.210 --> 00:13:41.900
So it recruited
small groups of women

00:13:41.900 --> 00:13:45.870
from communities to become
health promoters themselves.

00:13:45.870 --> 00:13:50.610
The groups traveled on
foot, went door to door,

00:13:50.610 --> 00:13:54.320
showing mothers how to
make these solutions.

00:13:54.320 --> 00:13:57.740
Later monitors went in and
checked how many of those

00:13:57.740 --> 00:14:00.770
mothers actually learn how
to make those solutions.

00:14:00.770 --> 00:14:05.540
And it was an iterative process,
there were failures plentiful.

00:14:05.540 --> 00:14:08.340
We learned as we went along.

00:14:08.340 --> 00:14:11.590
So staff tweaked their
approach as they went along.

00:14:11.590 --> 00:14:17.600
And one thing, sorry, one
example of our learning

00:14:17.600 --> 00:14:20.090
has been that when
the monitors went back

00:14:20.090 --> 00:14:22.610
after the first lot
of training happened,

00:14:22.610 --> 00:14:26.000
we found out that about
90% of these mothers

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:28.230
learned how to make
those solutions.

00:14:28.230 --> 00:14:30.590
So you would think
that was a success.

00:14:30.590 --> 00:14:34.430
But only 10% of them actually
gave it to their children

00:14:34.430 --> 00:14:36.680
when their children were sick.

00:14:36.680 --> 00:14:40.170
So people were scratching
their heads, what went wrong?

00:14:40.170 --> 00:14:43.370
A group of anthropologists
were sent to do some research,

00:14:43.370 --> 00:14:46.100
and they found out
was very interesting,

00:14:46.100 --> 00:14:47.690
not rocket science.

00:14:47.690 --> 00:14:51.860
But because the fathers weren't
involved in this process

00:14:51.860 --> 00:14:54.260
and they were the
key decision makers,

00:14:54.260 --> 00:14:56.780
so they actually
wouldn't let the mothers

00:14:56.780 --> 00:15:01.710
give this strange concoction to
their child when they got sick.

00:15:01.710 --> 00:15:05.120
So that's when the
next battle started.

00:15:05.120 --> 00:15:07.040
So we started training men.

00:15:07.040 --> 00:15:09.830
We started treating the fathers.

00:15:09.830 --> 00:15:11.990
And this is just
an example, but as

00:15:11.990 --> 00:15:15.380
other issues evolved, the
process was continuously

00:15:15.380 --> 00:15:18.440
modified, which led to
continuous improvement

00:15:18.440 --> 00:15:19.934
of the outcome itself.

00:15:19.934 --> 00:15:22.100
So BRAC then worked with
the Bangladeshi government,

00:15:22.100 --> 00:15:27.490
of course, to kind of
scale up nationwide.

00:15:27.490 --> 00:15:31.340
It basically, eventually,
went to every single household

00:15:31.340 --> 00:15:35.340
in Bangladesh, teaching
mothers how to make ORT.

00:15:35.340 --> 00:15:40.040
And that's a media
advocacy campaign

00:15:40.040 --> 00:15:44.120
followed to sustain
the effect, eventually.

00:15:44.120 --> 00:15:48.890
And just to kind of
finish off the story,

00:15:48.890 --> 00:15:53.090
there was this long article
on this in New Yorker magazine

00:15:53.090 --> 00:15:54.380
a couple of years ago.

00:15:54.380 --> 00:15:57.230
I'm just going to
read a few quotes.

00:15:57.230 --> 00:16:00.350
"Coaxing villagers to make this
solution with their own hands

00:16:00.350 --> 00:16:03.560
and explain the messages
in their own words

00:16:03.560 --> 00:16:05.330
while a trainer
observed and guided

00:16:05.330 --> 00:16:08.750
them achieved far more
than any public service

00:16:08.750 --> 00:16:11.680
ad or instructional
video could have done.

00:16:11.680 --> 00:16:15.170
Over time, the changes could
be sustained with television

00:16:15.170 --> 00:16:17.120
and radio and the
growth of demand

00:16:17.120 --> 00:16:19.280
led to the development
of a robust market

00:16:19.280 --> 00:16:22.340
for manufactured oral
rehydration salt.

00:16:22.340 --> 00:16:25.370
Three decades later
national surveys

00:16:25.370 --> 00:16:29.840
have found that almost 90% of
children with severe diarrhea

00:16:29.840 --> 00:16:31.610
were given the solution.

00:16:31.610 --> 00:16:35.120
Child deaths from diarrhea
plummeted more than 80%

00:16:35.120 --> 00:16:38.060
between 1980 and 2005.

00:16:38.060 --> 00:16:43.530
Bangladesh now has the highest
use of ORT in the world."

00:16:43.530 --> 00:16:47.220
So this is the
quote I love, and I

00:16:47.220 --> 00:16:51.870
think it's relevant to a lot
of you who are in technology.

00:16:51.870 --> 00:16:53.520
I mean, "we yearn
for frictionless,

00:16:53.520 --> 00:16:55.200
technology solutions.

00:16:55.200 --> 00:16:58.350
But people talking to
people is still the way

00:16:58.350 --> 00:17:00.030
norms and standards change."

00:17:02.760 --> 00:17:05.970
So there were some
early lessons in this,

00:17:05.970 --> 00:17:09.720
just to quickly summarize.

00:17:09.720 --> 00:17:11.290
Even 30 years ago.

00:17:11.290 --> 00:17:14.730
I know data is big now,
but even 30 years ago, data

00:17:14.730 --> 00:17:16.500
was king then at
that time as well.

00:17:16.500 --> 00:17:21.270
We constantly looked at
the numbers and evolved.

00:17:21.270 --> 00:17:24.869
Number two, social
innovation is not just

00:17:24.869 --> 00:17:26.859
about product innovation.

00:17:26.859 --> 00:17:31.560
It's about a continuous process
of adjustment and tweaking

00:17:31.560 --> 00:17:32.400
as you go along.

00:17:32.400 --> 00:17:35.050
It's about process
innovation as well.

00:17:35.050 --> 00:17:39.100
And number three, the
simpler your solution is,

00:17:39.100 --> 00:17:41.070
the easier it is to scale.

00:17:41.070 --> 00:17:43.800
So it's very, very
relevant to the part

00:17:43.800 --> 00:17:45.750
of the world we operate in.

00:17:45.750 --> 00:17:50.310
So fast forward
about 30 years later.

00:17:50.310 --> 00:17:54.280
So this is the second story
I'm going to talk about,

00:17:54.280 --> 00:18:01.150
which is more about when
high tech meets high touch.

00:18:01.150 --> 00:18:06.210
How do you get rural women,
and men of course, to trust

00:18:06.210 --> 00:18:10.710
and understand that mobile
money will improve their lives?

00:18:10.710 --> 00:18:16.350
Just to set a context,
there's a story

00:18:16.350 --> 00:18:19.950
that our microfinance
director talks about,

00:18:19.950 --> 00:18:23.520
that when we
introduced mobile money

00:18:23.520 --> 00:18:27.990
for our microfinance borrowers
to pay their loans on time,

00:18:27.990 --> 00:18:30.390
they would send the mobile
money through their phone

00:18:30.390 --> 00:18:33.120
and then they would
walk to our offices

00:18:33.120 --> 00:18:37.110
and come and make sure that
it actually has come through.

00:18:39.990 --> 00:18:44.400
Because in a country
where system often fails,

00:18:44.400 --> 00:18:47.310
you always want
that piece of paper,

00:18:47.310 --> 00:18:49.890
to make sure that this is
your proof that you actually

00:18:49.890 --> 00:18:51.610
have done it, you
don't actually have

00:18:51.610 --> 00:18:53.220
a lot of trust in your system.

00:18:53.220 --> 00:18:56.910
So it was actually
quite interesting,

00:18:56.910 --> 00:19:01.350
because to have them trust an
SMS message of confirmation

00:19:01.350 --> 00:19:04.570
was actually quite
a large shift.

00:19:04.570 --> 00:19:11.030
So the idea for
mobile money came in

00:19:11.030 --> 00:19:12.230
from a different context.

00:19:12.230 --> 00:19:18.470
I mean, I think when, 30
years later, Bangladesh

00:19:18.470 --> 00:19:22.850
has become a lot more urbanized,
it's not as rural anymore.

00:19:22.850 --> 00:19:25.970
Also people have become
a lot more mobile.

00:19:25.970 --> 00:19:28.940
They're traveling,
they're seasonal migrants

00:19:28.940 --> 00:19:32.697
who are coming back and forth
from villages to cities,

00:19:32.697 --> 00:19:34.280
they're working in
the cities and they

00:19:34.280 --> 00:19:37.500
want to send money
to their families.

00:19:37.500 --> 00:19:43.490
So there was a big need of safe,
reliable and affordable means

00:19:43.490 --> 00:19:45.140
of sending money back home.

00:19:45.140 --> 00:19:48.440
Of course, people found very
creative way of sending money.

00:19:48.440 --> 00:19:50.960
They send it through the
overnight bus service,

00:19:50.960 --> 00:19:54.410
they would send the money
through post-office,

00:19:54.410 --> 00:19:57.470
through selling airtime,
or physically carrying cash

00:19:57.470 --> 00:19:59.550
home every few months.

00:19:59.550 --> 00:20:03.200
But there was a big need or
something which actually did it

00:20:03.200 --> 00:20:04.910
quickly and reliably.

00:20:04.910 --> 00:20:08.780
So that's where the solution
came in, which is the Bkash,

00:20:08.780 --> 00:20:11.600
the mobile financial service.

00:20:11.600 --> 00:20:14.660
It inspired by the
success in East Africa,

00:20:14.660 --> 00:20:17.780
with M-Pesa and some
of the other companies

00:20:17.780 --> 00:20:19.760
that worked really
well in Africa.

00:20:19.760 --> 00:20:23.840
BRAC bank started Bkash
in 2011, with a mission

00:20:23.840 --> 00:20:27.680
towards including
the very bottom

00:20:27.680 --> 00:20:29.390
of the people, financially.

00:20:29.390 --> 00:20:32.810
Which means that actually,
not only just remittance

00:20:32.810 --> 00:20:36.260
but the big vision is that
introducing financial products

00:20:36.260 --> 00:20:39.120
and services that
works for the poor.

00:20:39.120 --> 00:20:42.320
So it was a great
fit for Bangladesh,

00:20:42.320 --> 00:20:45.170
because in Bangladesh
we have 90%

00:20:45.170 --> 00:20:49.400
of the household has
mobile phone, but only 30%

00:20:49.400 --> 00:20:50.870
has bank accounts.

00:20:50.870 --> 00:20:54.305
So if you can give
people with the phone,

00:20:54.305 --> 00:20:58.520
a bank account
should work wonders.

00:20:58.520 --> 00:21:01.300
But the problem was, just to--

00:21:01.300 --> 00:21:03.560
so before I get into
the problem a bit,

00:21:03.560 --> 00:21:05.720
just to give you an
understanding of how

00:21:05.720 --> 00:21:09.880
the solution worked, it's not
just a mobile to mobile money.

00:21:09.880 --> 00:21:12.500
There's a role of
an agent network

00:21:12.500 --> 00:21:13.530
within the organization.

00:21:13.530 --> 00:21:16.510
The idea is that a
rickshaw puller, say,

00:21:16.510 --> 00:21:20.480
who works in the city wants
to send money to his family,

00:21:20.480 --> 00:21:24.260
would actually go to an
agent, who would actually

00:21:24.260 --> 00:21:28.300
take the physical cash,
put it in his bank account,

00:21:28.300 --> 00:21:33.350
mobile money account, and then
they have the money transferred

00:21:33.350 --> 00:21:38.270
either directly to the
family or to an agent

00:21:38.270 --> 00:21:41.690
who's lives nearby to
the other family member

00:21:41.690 --> 00:21:43.250
and then the family
could use it.

00:21:43.250 --> 00:21:46.190
I mean if the money
was transferred

00:21:46.190 --> 00:21:49.430
to the bank account
of the sender,

00:21:49.430 --> 00:21:51.960
they could also use it for
other purposes as well,

00:21:51.960 --> 00:21:54.650
like buying things directly.

00:21:54.650 --> 00:21:58.280
But we don't have
ecosystem yet quite ready,

00:21:58.280 --> 00:22:01.770
so money's mostly being used
for remittance purposes.

00:22:01.770 --> 00:22:03.950
So this is how it worked.

00:22:03.950 --> 00:22:10.280
But the problem was that it
also went on to the delivery.

00:22:10.280 --> 00:22:13.910
Nobody knew Bkash, right, why
would people's trust Bkash?

00:22:13.910 --> 00:22:17.750
But everybody knew
BRAC at that time.

00:22:17.750 --> 00:22:21.680
And BRAC's, this is
just our operations

00:22:21.680 --> 00:22:26.100
in terms of where we are, in
terms of in the country itself.

00:22:26.100 --> 00:22:29.730
So we have a network
all across the country.

00:22:29.730 --> 00:22:34.490
So what we started to build
up was this agent network.

00:22:34.490 --> 00:22:39.560
And we worked with all
these borrowers that we have

00:22:39.560 --> 00:22:41.720
who actually own stores.

00:22:41.720 --> 00:22:45.530
So there are these small
shop owners who we went to

00:22:45.530 --> 00:22:47.480
and say that, you
know the community,

00:22:47.480 --> 00:22:51.470
the community knows you, are
you interested to be an agent?

00:22:51.470 --> 00:22:55.580
And initially, there was
not a lot of understanding,

00:22:55.580 --> 00:22:59.847
but people came along listening
to us, because we said,

00:22:59.847 --> 00:23:01.430
this is going to
work for you and this

00:23:01.430 --> 00:23:03.971
is going to work for everybody
else in the community as well.

00:23:03.971 --> 00:23:07.820
So 10,000 agents
signed up initially.

00:23:07.820 --> 00:23:11.720
And once we did it, and that's
where the early adopters came

00:23:11.720 --> 00:23:15.050
in, and then we started
working with growing

00:23:15.050 --> 00:23:17.210
the user base going forward.

00:23:17.210 --> 00:23:19.860
And the rest is
pretty much history,

00:23:19.860 --> 00:23:23.480
because Bkash has seen
very, very rapid expansion

00:23:23.480 --> 00:23:25.010
over the last five years.

00:23:25.010 --> 00:23:27.170
Just to show you
some numbers, this

00:23:27.170 --> 00:23:30.050
is a slightly dated
number, but we now have,

00:23:30.050 --> 00:23:32.630
it is now the largest
mobile financial service

00:23:32.630 --> 00:23:36.500
in terms of how many
people have direct accounts

00:23:36.500 --> 00:23:37.770
in the world right now.

00:23:37.770 --> 00:23:46.220
We have about, in Bangladesh,
we have about 41 million people

00:23:46.220 --> 00:23:50.750
with accounts, and about 80% of
them are Bkash account holders.

00:23:50.750 --> 00:23:53.900
You can see some of the
numbers, the rapid growth.

00:23:53.900 --> 00:23:58.010
We have almost close
to about $50 million

00:23:58.010 --> 00:23:59.300
being transacted daily.

00:24:01.940 --> 00:24:05.690
Now the agent network
boasts about 600,000

00:24:05.690 --> 00:24:08.830
around the country.

00:24:08.830 --> 00:24:12.590
It all just happened
in just four years.

00:24:12.590 --> 00:24:15.470
But we didn't want to
rest in this laurel,

00:24:15.470 --> 00:24:19.280
however, because as I said,
that the primary mission was

00:24:19.280 --> 00:24:22.580
to actually empower
the poor financially.

00:24:22.580 --> 00:24:24.440
So we looked at
the numbers again,

00:24:24.440 --> 00:24:29.000
and we saw that there were
far less women who signed up

00:24:29.000 --> 00:24:31.280
than men for Bkash accounts.

00:24:31.280 --> 00:24:34.550
And at the same time, people
were still accessing it

00:24:34.550 --> 00:24:38.210
primarily as through the agent
network not directly accessing

00:24:38.210 --> 00:24:39.050
themselves.

00:24:39.050 --> 00:24:41.930
And if you don't access
it directly yourself,

00:24:41.930 --> 00:24:45.170
then financial products and
services built up for you,

00:24:45.170 --> 00:24:47.720
you're not going to actually
see a lot of benefit for it.

00:24:47.720 --> 00:24:49.520
So I'm going to
see a small video

00:24:49.520 --> 00:24:51.770
in terms of how we took
that as a next step,

00:24:51.770 --> 00:24:54.909
in terms of increasing
the literacy for women.

00:24:54.909 --> 00:24:56.450
And this will probably
give you a bit

00:24:56.450 --> 00:25:02.810
of a glimpse of what we mean
by this high touch involvement.

