00:32:42.070 --> 00:32:47.260
We almost use Bangladesh as
a hub for experimentation.

00:32:47.260 --> 00:32:51.236
So the idea is that we
have these large sort

00:32:51.236 --> 00:32:53.110
of distribution channels
as I was mentioning,

00:32:53.110 --> 00:32:57.730
both in the financial sector,
education, and other sector,

00:32:57.730 --> 00:33:01.960
which lets us scale
up relatively easily.

00:33:01.960 --> 00:33:05.230
But what we lack is
we don't have so much

00:33:05.230 --> 00:33:07.600
technical prowess over there.

00:33:07.600 --> 00:33:10.240
And I think with the
infrastructure getting

00:33:10.240 --> 00:33:14.890
ready in the country
and also the region,

00:33:14.890 --> 00:33:18.541
it's not so much about all
the access is an issue,

00:33:18.541 --> 00:33:20.290
I think there's still
an issue but they're

00:33:20.290 --> 00:33:22.570
are going to be resolved
very quickly in the next two

00:33:22.570 --> 00:33:24.380
or three years.

00:33:24.380 --> 00:33:27.400
But what we lack is this
matchmaking to happen.

00:33:27.400 --> 00:33:31.600
I think basically we need
smarter products and services

00:33:31.600 --> 00:33:37.000
that are designed, built for,
thinking about those people

00:33:37.000 --> 00:33:38.830
in the next billion market.

00:33:38.830 --> 00:33:41.620
And then we need a very
smart distribution channel

00:33:41.620 --> 00:33:43.930
and this high touch
approach that we mentioned.

00:33:43.930 --> 00:33:46.990
So we have a social
innovation lab

00:33:46.990 --> 00:33:49.510
at BRAC, which looks at
some of these issues.

00:33:49.510 --> 00:33:53.170
This innovation fund, thing
that you saw-- innovation

00:33:53.170 --> 00:33:55.630
mobile money thing that
you saw on the video,

00:33:55.630 --> 00:33:57.910
it's being supported
by Gates Foundation,

00:33:57.910 --> 00:34:00.640
but this is something that
is run by the Innovation Lab

00:34:00.640 --> 00:34:04.570
So we are looking constantly
at external opportunities

00:34:04.570 --> 00:34:06.310
where we can make these matches.

00:34:06.310 --> 00:34:10.870
So I think particularly
in the next three

00:34:10.870 --> 00:34:13.480
or four years, I see a lot of
these kinds of partnerships

00:34:13.480 --> 00:34:16.960
being built. Because in
every sector, whether you

00:34:16.960 --> 00:34:21.429
call it health, education,
financial sector, agriculture,

00:34:21.429 --> 00:34:24.550
technologies is
becoming the disruptor.

00:34:24.550 --> 00:34:29.020
And the foster we adopt
and have those high touch

00:34:29.020 --> 00:34:32.770
approaches, I think there
are tremendous gains

00:34:32.770 --> 00:34:35.320
to be made in the coming days.

00:34:35.320 --> 00:34:37.989
SPEAKER 1: So is BRAC doing
any programs for startups

00:34:37.989 --> 00:34:40.389
in developing countries?

00:34:40.389 --> 00:34:42.280
ASIF SALEH: Yes.

00:34:42.280 --> 00:34:44.870
What we have started
in Bangladesh,

00:34:44.870 --> 00:34:52.840
we have had a number of things
both internally and externally,

00:34:52.840 --> 00:34:58.040
from the lab, we run a number of
innovation funds, very focused.

00:34:58.040 --> 00:35:00.700
So one thing we started,
Mobile Money Innovation Fund,

00:35:00.700 --> 00:35:03.640
where we asked our
large workforce,

00:35:03.640 --> 00:35:05.590
there was internal
competition, we

00:35:05.590 --> 00:35:08.440
said, give us your idea
on how mobile money can

00:35:08.440 --> 00:35:13.540
improve service delivery
for the poor people.

00:35:13.540 --> 00:35:16.990
That attracted a
lot of intrapreneurs

00:35:16.990 --> 00:35:20.020
to give their ideas,
and some of these ideas

00:35:20.020 --> 00:35:21.850
were piloted and expanded.

00:35:21.850 --> 00:35:24.160
Then we launched
another innovation fund

00:35:24.160 --> 00:35:26.200
for urban challenges.

00:35:26.200 --> 00:35:29.230
Urbanization, as you know, is
the biggest challenge, and now

00:35:29.230 --> 00:35:32.530
unplanned urbanization
in that part.

00:35:32.530 --> 00:35:36.520
So we asked for external
companies and innovators

00:35:36.520 --> 00:35:38.350
to give their ideas.

00:35:38.350 --> 00:35:42.160
So what we are doing now
is we are incubating them

00:35:42.160 --> 00:35:44.050
for about a year.

00:35:44.050 --> 00:35:45.820
So we are working
with them in terms

00:35:45.820 --> 00:35:49.390
of grounding their
ideas with our network,

00:35:49.390 --> 00:35:52.150
and then if some of
these actually stick,

00:35:52.150 --> 00:35:54.070
then we are going
to help them launch

00:35:54.070 --> 00:35:56.860
to become a full fledged
company and help them

00:35:56.860 --> 00:35:57.970
with initial financing.

00:35:57.970 --> 00:36:01.990
We are also expanding and
doing a lot of investments

00:36:01.990 --> 00:36:03.730
in terms of some of
the new startups.

00:36:03.730 --> 00:36:08.080
We just recently made an equity
investment in a tech startup

00:36:08.080 --> 00:36:11.440
called Maya, who's founder
is here, Ivy Russell.

00:36:14.200 --> 00:36:16.240
Maya is doing
great work in terms

00:36:16.240 --> 00:36:19.840
of creating a
community for women

00:36:19.840 --> 00:36:22.450
and providing them
basic services.

00:36:22.450 --> 00:36:24.990
So they have some
fantastic ideas

00:36:24.990 --> 00:36:27.060
on expansion going
forward as well.

00:36:27.060 --> 00:36:30.150
So the idea is not that BRAC
will have to do everything.

00:36:30.150 --> 00:36:32.620
The idea is that as long as
it is true to the mission,

00:36:32.620 --> 00:36:35.470
we will have a network
of organizations

00:36:35.470 --> 00:36:38.660
who will do the same
work that we want to do.

00:36:38.660 --> 00:36:42.990
And sometimes actually,
they can do it better.

00:36:42.990 --> 00:36:45.912
They're very focused
and they actually

00:36:45.912 --> 00:36:47.120
can do the work a lot better.

00:36:47.120 --> 00:36:51.160
So in the coming days, you'll
see a lot more expansion

00:36:51.160 --> 00:36:53.771
like this where we are going
to be investing in companies.

00:36:53.771 --> 00:36:55.270
AUDIENCE: So you
mentioned that BRAC

00:36:55.270 --> 00:36:56.561
has moved into other countries.

00:36:56.561 --> 00:36:58.510
So I'm curious what
changes and what

00:36:58.510 --> 00:37:01.990
stays the same when you take
programs to other countries?

00:37:01.990 --> 00:37:04.060
ASIF SALEH: Very good question.

00:37:04.060 --> 00:37:05.800
Actually a lot changes.

00:37:05.800 --> 00:37:11.090
We don't necessarily
take everything as is.

00:37:11.090 --> 00:37:14.090
And sometimes also, not
necessarily everything

00:37:14.090 --> 00:37:15.770
happens in Bangladesh
first, sometimes

00:37:15.770 --> 00:37:18.420
we also see the reverse
innovation as well.

00:37:18.420 --> 00:37:20.930
But I think what
we see in common

00:37:20.930 --> 00:37:26.390
is that across the new
countries we operate,

00:37:26.390 --> 00:37:29.810
these are mostly fragile
economies, or either

00:37:29.810 --> 00:37:32.600
post conflict countries.

00:37:32.600 --> 00:37:35.060
So we start, typically,
with micro microfinance,

00:37:35.060 --> 00:37:36.410
financial inclusion.

00:37:36.410 --> 00:37:38.780
And then as it starts
to build the network,

00:37:38.780 --> 00:37:42.470
then we go into other programs.

00:37:42.470 --> 00:37:45.170
In some areas that we
see that a common element

00:37:45.170 --> 00:37:49.350
is the role of the community,
the social capital.

00:37:49.350 --> 00:37:52.970
We have certain things very
common across the board.

00:37:52.970 --> 00:37:56.360
We tried to build them as
part of the program design.

00:37:56.360 --> 00:37:58.490
We have the notion of
the social network,

00:37:58.490 --> 00:38:00.560
we formed these clubs
with young people

00:38:00.560 --> 00:38:02.200
in Uganda which
works really well

00:38:02.200 --> 00:38:06.200
which, again, the genesis came
from a program in Bangladesh,

00:38:06.200 --> 00:38:08.960
but then it morphed
into something else.

00:38:08.960 --> 00:38:11.720
In Bangladesh we didn't have
financial microfinance built

00:38:11.720 --> 00:38:14.630
into the young people's clubs.

00:38:14.630 --> 00:38:18.500
Here in Uganda, when we saw that
this was actually a big need,

00:38:18.500 --> 00:38:20.480
because a lot of these--

00:38:20.480 --> 00:38:23.220
early pregnancy
was a big problem,

00:38:23.220 --> 00:38:25.010
and a lot of these
single mother they

00:38:25.010 --> 00:38:28.411
want to get into jobs and
livelihood generations.

00:38:28.411 --> 00:38:30.410
So we introduced the idea
of financial inclusion

00:38:30.410 --> 00:38:31.970
fairly early in these clubs.

00:38:31.970 --> 00:38:37.110
So that's how we actually
tweak the model over time.

00:38:37.110 --> 00:38:41.920
And we are now looking at taking
some of our skills learning,

00:38:41.920 --> 00:38:45.650
we have gone into the skills
program quite big in Bangladesh

00:38:45.650 --> 00:38:49.430
and we want to take some of
those in other parts of Africa

00:38:49.430 --> 00:38:51.050
as well.

00:38:51.050 --> 00:38:53.000
AUDIENCE: Thanks for
the wonderful talk.

00:38:53.000 --> 00:38:55.940
You talked about, when
you talked about Bkash,

00:38:55.940 --> 00:38:59.520
you mentioned
about trust factor.

00:38:59.520 --> 00:39:02.690
One of the area your
Bkash could be very useful

00:39:02.690 --> 00:39:04.580
of the remittance
is the e-commerce.

00:39:04.580 --> 00:39:08.150
And e-commerce has a huge amount
of trust factor deficiency.

00:39:08.150 --> 00:39:11.600
What do you learn in
the remittance sections

00:39:11.600 --> 00:39:13.640
of the Bkash transaction
that could be useful

00:39:13.640 --> 00:39:17.540
for e-commerce as well in
Bangladesh or outside as well?

00:39:17.540 --> 00:39:21.050
ASIF SALEH: So I think
e-commerce in Bangladesh

00:39:21.050 --> 00:39:24.680
is starting to take off, but
there are still lots of issues,

00:39:24.680 --> 00:39:29.630
because the ecosystem
is not quite built yet.

00:39:29.630 --> 00:39:33.530
You still have problems with
the delivery of packages

00:39:33.530 --> 00:39:37.880
and so the distribution
channel is not quite there.

00:39:37.880 --> 00:39:41.320
But I think we are
seeing, if you look at,

00:39:41.320 --> 00:39:44.060
although the numbers are fairly
small in the early stage,

00:39:44.060 --> 00:39:49.070
if you look at the numbers,
they look very, very promising.

00:39:49.070 --> 00:39:55.300
But interestingly, we
have a large retail chain

00:39:55.300 --> 00:39:59.600
called Aarong, those of you
from Bangladesh know Aarong.

00:39:59.600 --> 00:40:03.450
It actually started aarong.com
about three years ago.

00:40:03.450 --> 00:40:05.150
And from some of
the numbers there,

00:40:05.150 --> 00:40:09.440
we see not different
from India, people still

00:40:09.440 --> 00:40:15.090
are not very comfortable in
doing electronic purchasing.

00:40:15.090 --> 00:40:17.525
They are still doing
cash on delivery.

00:40:17.525 --> 00:40:21.740
The cash on delivery is not
good for e-commerce sector,

00:40:21.740 --> 00:40:24.990
but people are still more
comfortable in doing that.

00:40:24.990 --> 00:40:29.270
And so in aarong.com's number,
about 70% of the purchases

00:40:29.270 --> 00:40:31.760
still happen through COD's.

00:40:31.760 --> 00:40:36.950
And Bkash numbers are
relatively smaller,

00:40:36.950 --> 00:40:40.640
but I think that's also due to
the fact of user experience.

00:40:40.640 --> 00:40:43.010
I think Bkash is
launching a new app

00:40:43.010 --> 00:40:45.320
in this year, which is
going to make the user

00:40:45.320 --> 00:40:48.650
experience a lot better.

00:40:48.650 --> 00:40:53.900
But once that happens,
the Bkash should take off

00:40:53.900 --> 00:40:56.660
more quickly than credit card,
because credit card is more

00:40:56.660 --> 00:41:01.340
difficult. I think nobody
is hand-holding anybody

00:41:01.340 --> 00:41:04.010
in e-commerce, I think
that's the big factor.

00:41:04.010 --> 00:41:06.680
But this notion of
associated e-commerce

00:41:06.680 --> 00:41:11.161
has started in India, which
basically uses intermediary,

00:41:11.161 --> 00:41:11.660
right?

00:41:11.660 --> 00:41:15.680
So you have these centers
where people can go to

00:41:15.680 --> 00:41:18.770
and they have access to internet
and laptops and all that,

00:41:18.770 --> 00:41:20.960
and they help you browse.

00:41:20.960 --> 00:41:24.650
This is what you have available,
and then they let you buy it,

00:41:24.650 --> 00:41:27.380
and the packages actually
come to that center.

00:41:27.380 --> 00:41:30.860
And so they take a small cut
and then they make the fee.

00:41:30.860 --> 00:41:34.100
So that's becoming also, that
has also started to happen.

00:41:34.100 --> 00:41:36.460
So I think same kind
of hand-holding,

00:41:36.460 --> 00:41:39.200
so somebody to take them through
that experience initially,

00:41:39.200 --> 00:41:40.740
that needs to happen.

00:41:40.740 --> 00:41:42.904
So I think that that's
interesting learning,

00:41:42.904 --> 00:41:44.320
because right now
we are just kind

00:41:44.320 --> 00:41:47.180
of assuming that its just
going to happen automatically,

00:41:47.180 --> 00:41:48.180
and it's not.

00:41:48.180 --> 00:41:49.466
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

